<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="193" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="193">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="193">
<bibRefCitation author="de Sagarra, I" journalOrPublisher="Mitteilungen der Muenchner Entomologischen Gesellschaft" pageId="0" pageNumber="193" refId="B21" refString="de Sagarra, I, 1926. Anotacions a la lepidopterologia ibe'rica IV. Butlleti de la Institucio Catalana d'Historia Natural (2)6: 128-139." title="Anotacions a la lepidopterologia ibe'rica IV. Butlleti de la Institucio Catalana d'Historia Natural (2) 6: 128 - 139." year="1926">de Sagarra (1926)</bibRefCitation>
proposed this name as a &quot;rassa = race&quot; of 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. trivia" pageId="0" pageNumber="193" rank="species" species="trivia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="193">M. trivia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
([Denis &amp; Schiffermullar], 1775). The term &quot;rassa = race&quot; which was employed by de Sagarra in 1926 was often used in the current sense of subspecies. As a result, the first line of article 45.6 (
<bibRefCitation author="ICZN" journalOrPublisher="Internationale Entomologische Zeitschrift" pageId="0" pageNumber="193" publicationUrl="http://www.iczn.org/iczn/index.jsp" refId="B47" refString="ICZN, 1999. International Code of Zoological Nomenclature. Fourth edition. London. [available online at http://www.iczn.org/iczn/index.jsp" title="International Code of Zoological Nomenclature. Fourth edition. London. [available online at" url="http://www.iczn.org/iczn/index.jsp" year="1999">ICZN 1999</bibRefCitation>
) - the rank denoted by a species-group name following a binomen is subspecific - is applied here, it is thus available as subspecific. 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1365-2311.1941.tb01045.x" author="Higgins, LG" journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the Royal Entomological Society of London" pageId="0" pageNumber="193" pagination="175 - 365" refId="B42" refString="Higgins, LG, 1941. An illustrated catalogue of the Palearctic Melitaea (Lep. Rhopalocera). Transactions of the Royal Entomological Society of London 91 (7): 175 - 365, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1365-2311.1941.tb01045.x" title="An illustrated catalogue of the Palearctic Melitaea (Lep. Rhopalocera)." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1365-2311.1941.tb01045.x" volume="91" year="1941">Higgins (1941)</bibRefCitation>
synonymised it with 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. trivia subsp. pseudodidyma" pageId="0" pageNumber="193" rank="subSpecies" species="trivia" subSpecies="pseudodidyma">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="193">M. trivia pseudodidyma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Rebel, 1905 but he reconsidered it as a valid subspecies in his subsequent books. 
<bibRefCitation author="Garcia-Barros, E" journalOrPublisher="Museo Nacional de Ciencias Naturales, CSIC. Madrid" pageId="0" pageNumber="193" refId="B31" refString="Garcia-Barros, E, Munguira, M, Stefanescu, C, Vives, MA, 2013. . LepidopteraPapilionoidea. In: Ramos MA et al. (Eds) Fauna Iberica, vol. 37. Museo Nacional de Ciencias Naturales, CSIC. Madrid" title=". LepidopteraPapilionoidea. In: Ramos MA et al. (Eds) Fauna Iberica, vol. 37." year="2013">
<normalizedToken originalValue="GarcÃ­a-Barros">Garcia-Barros</normalizedToken>
et al. (2013)
</bibRefCitation>
made a comment in Fauna 
<normalizedToken originalValue="IbÃ©rica">Iberica</normalizedToken>
that &quot;the orange color of the Iberian specimens is lighter than those from other European areas; those have been attributed to subspecies &quot; 
<taxonomicName authorityName="de Sagarra" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Melitaea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Melitaea ignasiti" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="193" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ignasiti">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="193">Melitaea ignasiti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
de Sagarra, 1926&quot;, which, however, does not seem significantly different. Furthermore, it does not seem significantly differentiated from a genetic point of view (Wahlberg pers. comm.).&quot; The taxon 
<taxonomicName authorityName="de Sagarra" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Melitaea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Melitaea ignasiti" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="193" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ignasiti">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="193">Melitaea ignasiti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was reinstated as a valid species by 
<bibRefCitation author="van Oorschot, H" journalOrPublisher="Tshikolovets Publications, Pardubice" pageId="0" pageNumber="193" refId="B93" refString="van Oorschot, H, Coutsis, JG, 2014. The genus Melitaea Fabricius, 1807 (Lepidoptera, Nymphalidae, Nymphalinae). Taxonomy and systematics with special reference to the male genitalia. Tshikolovets Publications, Pardubice" title="The genus Melitaea Fabricius, 1807 (Lepidoptera, Nymphalidae, Nymphalinae). Taxonomy and systematics with special reference to the male genitalia." year="2014">van Oorschot and Coutsis (2014)</bibRefCitation>
, and this was accepted by Macia et al. (2015) who designated lectotype and paralectotypes. Therefore, specimens at ZMH are by default paralectotypes. However, most other recent authors (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation author="Kudrna, O" journalOrPublisher="Spolecnost pro Ochranu Motylu, Prachatice, CZ" pageId="0" pageNumber="193" refId="B57" refString="Kudrna, O, 2019. Distribution of Butterflies and Skippers in Europe (Lepidoptera: Rhopalocera, Grypocera). 24 years Mapping European Butterflies (1995-2019), Final Report. Spolecnost pro Ochranu Motylu, Prachatice, CZ" title="Distribution of Butterflies and Skippers in Europe (Lepidoptera: Rhopalocera, Grypocera). 24 years Mapping European Butterflies (1995 - 2019), Final Report." year="2019">Kudrna 2019</bibRefCitation>
) treat this taxon as a synonym to 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. trivia" pageId="0" pageNumber="193" rank="species" species="trivia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="193">M. trivia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, because there is no evidence for species status. Even Oorschot and Coutsis (2014) mention intermediates indicating hybridisation. It should be noted that the species name is not mentioned in the latest European checklist (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.811.28712" author="Wiemers, M" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="193" pagination="9 - 45" refId="B118" refString="Wiemers, M, Balletto, E, Dinca, V, Fric, ZF, Lamas, G, Lukhtanov, V, Munguira, ML, van Swaay, CAM, Vila, R, Vliegenthart, A, Wahlberg, N, Verovnik, R, 2018. An updated checklist of the European Butterflies (Lepidoptera, Papilionoidea). ZooKeys 811: 9 - 45, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.811.28712" title="An updated checklist of the European Butterflies (Lepidoptera, Papilionoidea)." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.811.28712" volume="811" year="2018">Wiemers et al. 2018</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
